 Deploying Machine Learning Models with Docker and Flask
Objectives
Design and containerize a Flask-based REST API that serves predictions from a trained scikit-learn model
Integrate a PostgreSQL database container to persist prediction requests and results
Orchestrate multi-container ML infrastructure using Docker Compose with load balancing
Prerequisites
Comfort working in a Linux/Ubuntu terminal including file editing, directory navigation, and reading command output
Familiarity with Python scripting and the concept of REST APIs (HTTP methods, JSON payloads, status codes)
Basic understanding of what a trained machine learning model is and what inference means
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Environment
Requirement 1
Install Docker Engine, Docker Compose plugin, and Python 3 with pip on the Ubuntu instance, then confirm each tool is operational before proceeding.

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release python3 python3-pip

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-compose-plugin
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
Official installation reference if the URL above changes: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â this means the file contains a literal backslash or a broken line.
Inspect the file with cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â it must be a single unbroken line; delete it with sudo rm /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list and recreate it using the heredoc form shown above.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
