Task 2: Build and Containerize the ML Prediction Service
Requirement 1
Design and implement a complete ML prediction service from scratch. The service must: train an iris classification model using scikit-learn and persist it to disk; expose a Flask REST API with at minimum a /health endpoint (GET), a /predict endpoint (POST accepting a JSON body with a features key containing a list of four floats), and a /predictions/history endpoint (GET); and package the entire application in a Docker image built from a Dockerfile you write without using any pre-built application images beyond python:3.11-slim.

Acceptance criteria:

docker build -t ml-api:v1 . completes without error, and docker run --rm -p 5000:5000 ml-api:v1 starts the server; curl -s http://localhost:5000/health returns HTTP 200 with a JSON body containing a status field set to "healthy" and a model_loaded field set to true.
curl -s -X POST http://localhost:5000/predict -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"features":[5.1,3.5,1.4,0.2]}' returns HTTP 200 with a JSON body containing predicted_class (a non-empty string), prediction (an integer 0, 1, or 2), and probabilities (an object with three keys summing to 1.0 within floating-point tolerance); sending a body with fewer than four features must return HTTP 400.
Requirement 2
Extend the project to a multi-container architecture using a single docker-compose.yml file you author from scratch. The architecture must include: the ML API service (two replicas on distinct host ports), a PostgreSQL 15 container that initialises a predictions table on first start using an SQL init script you write, and an Nginx container acting as a round-robin load balancer across the two API replicas. The API must write every successful /predict call to the predictions table and serve stored records from /predictions/history.

Acceptance criteria:

docker compose up -d starts all four containers (postgres, two ml-api instances, nginx) with all showing healthy or running status in docker compose ps; curl -s http://localhost/health returns HTTP 200 through the Nginx proxy, and repeating the request ten times distributes traffic across both API containers as confirmed by differing container_id or hostname values in the response body.
After sending five POST requests to http://localhost/predict with valid feature arrays, curl -s "http://localhost/predictions/history?limit=5" returns a JSON array of exactly five records each containing id, timestamp, features, predicted_class, and probabilities fields; connecting directly to PostgreSQL with docker exec -it <postgres-container> psql -U postgres -d ml_predictions -c "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM predictions;" returns a count of five or more.
Task 3: Validate End-to-End Behaviour and Resilience
Requirement 1
Write a Python test script from scratch (no testing framework required â plain requests calls with assert statements are sufficient) that exercises the full API surface: health check, single prediction for each of the three iris classes using known representative feature vectors, a malformed request that must return 400, and prediction history retrieval. The script must exit with code 0 on full success and code 1 on any assertion failure, printing a clear pass or fail message for each test case.

Acceptance criteria:

Running python3 tests/test_api.py against the live Docker Compose stack exits with code 0 and prints a pass confirmation for every test case including the health check, all three class predictions, the 400-error case, and the history retrieval.
The prediction for feature vector [5.1, 3.5, 1.4, 0.2] must resolve to "setosa", [6.2, 2.9, 4.3, 1.3] must resolve to "versicolor", and [7.3, 2.9, 6.3, 1.8] must resolve to "virginica" â these are deterministic given a fixed random seed in the model training script; if any class is wrong the script must print the actual vs expected value and exit with code 1.
Requirement 2
Demonstrate container resilience by stopping one of the two ML API containers while the stack is running, sending ten prediction requests through the Nginx load balancer, then restarting the stopped container and confirming the full stack recovers without data loss.

Acceptance criteria:

With one API container stopped, all ten curl -s -X POST http://localhost/predict requests return HTTP 200 (Nginx must route all traffic to the surviving replica); docker compose ps shows one container in a stopped or restarting state and one running.
After docker compose start <stopped-service> the restarted container reaches a healthy state within 60 seconds confirmed by curl -s http://localhost:<direct-port>/health returning "model_loaded": true; docker exec into PostgreSQL confirms the total row count in predictions equals the sum of all requests sent before and after the outage with no gaps in the id sequence.
Expected Outcomes
A fully containerised ML inference stack runs on your EC2 instance with load balancing, database persistence, and automated health checks all verified by your own test script.
You can stop, restart, and scale individual containers without losing prediction history or breaking the API surface exposed through Nginx.
Conclusion
This lab required you to design every component of a production-style ML deployment from scratch: model training and serialisation, a REST API, container images, database schema, orchestration, load balancing, and automated validation. The patterns you applied here â separating concerns across containers, persisting state in a dedicated data service, and routing traffic through a reverse proxy â are the same patterns used in real ML platform engineering. Extend this foundation by adding authentication, model versioning, or a monitoring sidecar as your next self-directed challenge.
